{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module-to-client handoff (payload assembly + API call wrapper), so a pure unit test can miss dropped/misnamed fields at wiring boundaries (MOCK-MISS). Real OS/network is not required; an in-process fake client that captures outbound payload is sufficient (INTEGRATION-BRAKE a=no). Correctness does not depend on model output content (b=no), and there is no multi-agent chain (c/d=no). Rejected System/Agentic because behavior text is about request construction, not live infrastructure or model judgment.","test_description":"Wire classifier module to a fake provider client, invoke classify(), and assert captured request includes every taxonomy label exactly once in the outbound payload sent by the module.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is a local normalization/validation rule on one returned value; no real boundary interaction is required to trigger the failure. MOCK-MISS does not force escalation because behavior text is about mapping an out-of-taxonomy label to a sentinel value. Rejected Integration because no concrete handoff/state propagation requirement appears in the behavior text.","test_description":"Call the normalization/classification decision function with taxonomy {legal, technical, financial, other} and raw label \"medical\"; assert final label is \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Determinism of a normalization step is a pure function property (same input -> same output). No external infrastructure or model decision is needed, so higher levels add cost without increasing failure detection for this behavior. Rejected Integration because the behavior text scopes strictly to the normalization step.","test_description":"Run normalization repeatedly with the same raw API response fixture (including casing/whitespace variants already fixed in fixture) and assert identical final label every run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires repeated live API calls and depends on real model/provider outputs over time (LLM-DEP=yes). A stub would always be consistent and can hide real inconsistency caused by model nondeterminism or provider-side drift (MOCK-HIDE). Rejected Integration/System as minimum because behavior text requires validating consistency under real AI responses, not only transport/process behavior.","test_description":"Execute N repeated calls against the real provider for the same document+taxonomy, log raw provider responses and final labels, and assert label changes only when raw provider output changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.17,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure can occur at boundary between tokenizer/budget policy and dispatch path (e.g., budget computed but still dispatched), so module wiring must be exercised (MOCK-MISS=yes at module boundary). Real OS/network/subprocess is unnecessary (a=no), model output quality irrelevant (b=no), no multi-agent chain (c/d=no). Rejected System/Agentic due behavior text focusing on pre-dispatch enforcement logic.","test_description":"Configure a small token budget, run classify() with an over-budget document using fake provider client, and assert policy outcome (truncate or reject) plus that dispatch occurs or is blocked exactly per policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This executes a real AI API call and asserts on provider-reported token usage, which a stub can mask (MOCK-HIDE). Per rule, paths that pass through real AI/ML APIs default Agentic unless exclusively testing wrapper infrastructure; here assertion is about provider-produced usage values, not just routing. Rejected Integration because deterministic fake usage cannot reveal provider-side tokenization/model changes.","test_description":"Call the real provider with representative document(s), read returned usage metadata, and assert reported total/request tokens are <= configured budget for each call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.22,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Core failure is retry orchestration across module + API client error mapping + backoff policy; this is a local module interaction boundary (MOCK-MISS=yes). Real network/OS timing primitives are not required if fake client and controllable clock/timer are used (a=no). No dependence on model output content (b=no) and no multi-agent pipeline (c/d=no). Rejected System/Agentic because behavior text is transport error handling, not live infrastructure fidelity or model judgment.","test_description":"Use a fake provider that returns rate-limit error then success; verify module delays per policy (with fake clock), retries, and ultimately returns successful label instead of surfacing the first error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0}}]}
